WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.560
 [MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:24.840
 Can you walk us up to the inspirations and the history

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:31.460
 of how perhaps ABC got so good at OO?

00:00:31.460 --> 00:00:41.120
 So ABC was actually not object oriented.

00:00:41.120 --> 00:00:47.320
 ABC had a fixed set of data types.

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:54.040
 The data types were composable, like you

00:00:54.040 --> 00:01:00.600
 could have, say, a list of integers or a list of strings.

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:04.360
 And those would share the operations on lists.

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:09.600
 But there was no concept of class.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:16.040
 There was no concept of users defining classes.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:20.380
 There was no concept of subclassing,

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:24.880
 either in the implementation or for the built-in types.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:30.480
 So ABC had a bunch of really convenient to use primitives.

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:33.920
 They did a lot of work for you, but they weren't really OO.

00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:34.960
 That's correct.

00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:44.480
 And they insisted that there was only a single numeric type,

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:50.560
 in part so that they could sort of not deal

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:55.960
 with the complicated hierarchy of integers and floats

00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:59.240
 and rationals and sort of--

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:01.320
 So then, but when you started Python,

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.680
 you had like object orientation very front of mind,

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:07.400
 not just a convenient set of primitives,

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:10.240
 but a convenient set of object-based primitives.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:13.480
 Where-- did you read that in it?

00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:14.360
 Yeah.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.620
 Or did you read that somewhere else?

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:22.160
 I was familiar with C++.

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:22.720
 Yeah.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:28.840
 And I think that might have been the only object-oriented

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:31.200
 language that I knew at the time.

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:34.200
 At least, I can't think of any--

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:38.280
 well, I own a big book about Simula,

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:43.240
 which is sort of the granddaddy of all object-oriented

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:46.040
 languages, I don't think I ever managed

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:49.440
 to get my hands on a Simula compiler.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:52.640
 And I have to admit, I also only skimmed the book

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:55.840
 because it was actually sort of--

00:02:55.840 --> 00:02:58.160
 Had you written C++ before?

00:02:58.160 --> 00:02:59.080
 Yes.

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:02.360
 Like what kind of-- how much have you written C++?

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:06.320
 Enough to invent automatic--

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:07.600
 I forget what they're called.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:11.320
 The pointers that are like automatically ref counted.

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:13.600
 So yeah, I forget, C++--

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:14.600
 They're a standard--

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:17.040
 --counting on top of C++ so that you would not

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:20.200
 lose your sanity while working in C++?

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:23.560
 No, because I was very familiar with ref counts.

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:27.000
 Because ABC's implementation is written in C,

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.200
 and everything uses reference counting.

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:34.120
 And it works out better in ABC because there

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:38.040
 are no cycles possible in the data types.

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:41.240
 Because there are no mutable data types.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:47.240
 You can't have an object that contains itself or references

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:50.680
 itself directly or indirectly in ABC.

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:54.200
 I don't think that I sort of realized

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:57.140
 all the details of why that is important.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:04:01.560
 And I didn't care, because pragmatically, those things

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:05.520
 aren't always as important as they seem to be theoretically.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.400
 But anyway, I was very familiar with reference counting

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:13.840
 in C and how it was used for ABC.

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:16.320
 I think that that's where I learned about it.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:20.840
 And I didn't hear much about it elsewhere.

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:26.160
 Then at some point when I was teaching myself C++--

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:28.840
 this must have been in the mid '80s--

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:31.400
 one of the things I tried was--

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:34.560
 I mean, my experience with ABC and reference counts

00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:38.600
 in the implementation was that it was very error prone.

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:45.640
 We regularly had to sort of deal with bugs in the implementation

00:04:45.640 --> 00:04:51.400
 where we either leaked memory or sort of crashed

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:53.840
 because we had freed things early.

00:04:53.840 --> 00:04:55.520
 And it was always like, oh, there's

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:58.080
 a missing ink ref or dec ref.

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:01.320
 And of course, the missing dec ref

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:05.080
 is much harder to debug because you leak a byte here

00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:07.200
 and you leak a byte there and nobody notices.

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.480
 Because people didn't write large applications in ABC.

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:22.360
 So anyway, someone probably put me on the idea of in C++,

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:26.000
 you can override primitive operations to the extent

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.640
 that you can build automatic reference counting.

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:36.960
 And I built that for some toy application

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:45.840
 and played with it and realized that it didn't work right.

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:49.040
 The problem was that it was like--

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:52.920
 and I probably didn't know enough C++ at the time,

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:57.840
 or possibly C++ hadn't developed certain subtle mechanisms

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:01.200
 like move operations.

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:06.000
 It was very crude, like overloading assignment.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.280
 That was basically what I did.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:15.040
 And so I found that where if I had handwritten reference count

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:19.120
 operations, I would sort of know, OK, this object

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:23.440
 is owned here, so we pass it to some function.

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:27.160
 That function doesn't have to increment the reference count

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:30.920
 just because it's using that object because it's not

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:34.280
 going anywhere as long as the color of that function

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:36.040
 has a reference to it.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:38.520
 On the other hand, the automatic reference counting,

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:42.880
 as I had implemented it using C++,

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:46.040
 would say, oh, we're passing this thing as an argument

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:48.880
 to a function, so increment the reference count.

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:51.560
 Oh, that function returns, decrement the reference count.

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:54.080
 So there was much, much, much more reference counting

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:57.920
 activity and sort of that part I didn't like.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:00.880
 And so Python still does it manually

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:03.720
 and is written in C, not in C++.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:09.520
 But somehow, I picked up the idea of vtables,

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:14.680
 or at least arrays of pointers to functions,

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:19.720
 as a handy way to implement objects.

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:24.320
 And actually, initially for the first probably six months,

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:28.840
 Python was not object oriented.

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:33.280
 And so very few people saw that, like a handful of my coworkers

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:35.000
 saw that.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.400
 And the implementation had this notion

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:44.800
 of you can implement an object type

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:47.600
 by putting a bunch of function pointers

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:51.400
 and a bit of other information in a standard structure that

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:52.960
 describes the type.

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:55.680
 I called it a type, not an object.

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:59.560
 So in a way that you were emulating C++ as a way

00:07:59.560 --> 00:08:03.040
 of creating perception of object oriented programming

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:05.120
 without truly being an object.

00:08:05.120 --> 00:08:05.640
 Yeah.

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:08.400
 Oh, and wait a second.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:11.560
 There is another step that I just missed.

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:23.880
 So in around '88, I spent a summer as an intern at DexCirc.

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:27.680
 And I talked to the designers and inventors

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:31.160
 of a language named Modula 3.

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:37.840
 And they were putting the last proof reading efforts

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:40.320
 for the Modula 3 report.

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:45.120
 But they had built a Modula 2 and 1/2 compiler.

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:46.600
 They called it Modula 2 Plus.

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:53.360
 And in their documentation, either the draft

00:08:53.360 --> 00:08:59.560
 of the Modula 3 manual or the internal Modula 2 Plus manual,

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:04.400
 I learned this concept of how Modula 2 Plus and 3

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:09.520
 do kind of not quite object orientation.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.080
 And I think they meant it as sort of a reaction

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:17.000
 to how it was done in C++.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.520
 They said Modula 3 is not actually

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:22.000
 an object oriented language.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:28.800
 But the sort of the key part of object oriented use

00:09:28.800 --> 00:09:36.360
 where you define a class through a bunch of functions

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:41.840
 and the notation where you say object dot method

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:47.320
 and then the arguments instead of function and then the object

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:49.520
 and then the rest of the arguments.

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:54.680
 They said if you use that notation object dot or thing

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:59.280
 dot dot method paren and then arguments,

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:06.240
 thing had to be something that had a type.

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:09.920
 I think it was a structure type that had a bunch of function

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:11.840
 pointers in it.

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:18.600
 And so the method names were simply

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:23.080
 fields or members of that structure in Modula 3.

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:27.080
 And so to create the equivalent of a class,

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:33.520
 you defined a structure that had a bunch of function pointers.

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:34.480
 They were all typed.

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:36.000
 So you could say this is a function

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.240
 that takes one argument of this type and it returns blah, blah.

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:43.080
 And then a bunch of those with names.

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:46.000
 And the trick was if the compiler sort of noticed

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.320
 that you were using that and then you were calling it,

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:53.280
 it would say, oh, we're going to insert

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:59.080
 the thing whose method you just used as the very first parameter

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:00.440
 to the function.

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:04.600
 This is where Python's explicit self comes from.

00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:10.840
 And so that is all Modula 3's design that I copied.

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:15.960
 And so originally in Python, I didn't have a user level

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:19.280
 notation to even do that.

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:22.680
 The type system was only extensible

00:11:22.680 --> 00:11:26.120
 by writing a C extension.

00:11:26.120 --> 00:11:26.880
 Oh.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:30.840
 And so the author of--

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:33.280
 The class keyword, what we think of as a class keyword,

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:36.760
 was not there for a month and a half.

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:40.440
 In the first probably five or six months, it wasn't there.

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:48.680
 And I think we had an intern who knew C++ better

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:52.360
 or who somehow had the right--

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:53.200
 who knows?

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:55.800
 He was younger than me.

00:11:55.800 --> 00:12:04.160
 And he said, hey, if you want to give users the ability

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:06.720
 to define their own classes, here

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:08.680
 is a hack how you could do it.

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:12.400
 You add this little bit of syntax,

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:14.760
 and then you map it to this structure

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:18.560
 at the implementation time, and it all works.

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:20.000
 And that's 5.1c.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:21.640
 And yeah.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:24.320
 And so everything else was working.

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:30.160
 We had a working interpreter with a REPL, and integers,

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:33.560
 and floats, and strings, and tuples, and lists,

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:38.400
 and dictionaries, and functions, and types

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:42.440
 that were sort of internal things.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:47.600
 I think even then you could ask for the type of an object.

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:53.040
 Did you, at the time, in these first six months of Python,

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:57.440
 did you feel like you were doing core research

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:00.840
 on what object orientation was going to mean in the future?

00:13:00.840 --> 00:13:01.340
 No.

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:02.800
 Or were you just--

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:08.120
 I was just hacking together an implementation of a language

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:11.280
 that I didn't know where it was going.

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:14.320
 I obviously spent enough time on it

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:21.760
 that I was hoping it would go somewhere.

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:22.260
 But--

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:24.080
 You didn't think of yourself as like a--

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:25.720
 that you were going to someday write

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:29.040
 a paper about how object orientation should be done.

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:31.360
 You weren't thinking like a researcher would think.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:33.080
 Definitely not that.

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:34.280
 You were just solving problems.

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:35.720
 I was not a researcher.

00:13:35.720 --> 00:13:37.800
 I was a programmer.

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:42.280
 I do not have a PhD.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:47.680
 I was employed by CWI as a programmer.

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:50.360
 Do you now even think maybe that you

00:13:50.360 --> 00:13:54.440
 made a profound contribution?

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:56.480
 You're the first person to tell me that.

00:13:56.480 --> 00:14:02.280
 And I'm not sure that I totally believe it.

00:14:02.280 --> 00:14:08.680
 I would say that the Modula 3 inventors sort of

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:14.800
 made that contribution because they were much more sort

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:19.760
 of researchy types, theory types.

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:24.360
 They thought long and deep about all the sort

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:27.840
 of theoretical and eventual repercussions

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:29.200
 of designs like that.

00:14:29.200 --> 00:14:36.040
 And I was happy to implement something even if there were

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:39.360
 edge cases where it would just not do the right thing at all,

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:45.320
 like until we finally, after about a decade or so,

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:49.560
 added a cyclic garbage collector to the language.

00:14:49.560 --> 00:14:53.280
 Python would leak memory irretrievably

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:58.400
 in many situations where you had created a cycle

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:04.480
 and then lost the last pointer into the cycle from outside it.

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:09.000
 And it took a very long time before our users convinced us

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.280
 that there were some edge cases where that was actually

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:17.080
 a real problem and there was no good existing solution.

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:20.080
 [MUSIC PLAYING]

00:15:34.480 --> 00:15:37.240
 (dramatic music)

